
[1]brail

   BRAIL, n.

   1. A piece of leather to bind up a hawk's wing.

   2. In navigation, brails are ropes passing through pulleys,on the mizen
   mast and yard, and fastened to the aftmost leech of the sail in
   different places, to truss it up close. Also, all ropes employed to
   haul up the bottoms, lower corners and skirts of the other great sails,
   for the more ready furling of them.

   BRAIL, v.t. To brail up, is to haul up into the brails, or to truss up
                              with the brails.
